      <hedline>
        <hl1>DiCaprio the Journalist</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John E Colbert letter on Maureen Dowd's Apr 9 column defends Leonardo DiCaprio's interview with Pres Clinton</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''American Beauty'' (column, April 9), by Maureen Dowd:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''American Beauty'' (column, April 9), by Maureen Dowd:</p>
        <p>If ''journalism'' means exploring and reporting issues and events of import, and ''entertainment'' means finding ways to amuse and interest an audience, then in comparing network journalists' choice and saturation coverage of ''big events'' of recent years -- O. J., LewinskyClinton and Elian -- with Leonardo DiCaprio's interview of President Clinton on the subject of global warming, Mr. DiCaprio surfaces as the journalist, while network coverage seems to hover more in the entertainment realm.</p>
        <p>JOHN E. COLBERT  Chicago, April 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
